  "prompt": "Why does ISKCON deny Lord Shiva's Supremacy?",
  "response": "The International Society for Krishna Consciousness (ISKCON), which follows the teachings of the Gaudiya Vaishnavism tradition, primarily emphasizes the worship of Lord Krishna as the Supreme God. In this theological framework, Lord Krishna is viewed as the original source of all beings and deities, including Lord Shiva. \n\nIn Gaudiya Vaishnavism, while Lord Shiva is respected as a great devotee and an important figure within the Vedic tradition, he is not considered the Supreme Being in the same way that Krishna is. The philosophy posits that all other deities, including Shiva, are ultimately subordinate to Krishna and are manifestations or expansions of His divine energy.\n\nISKCON's position is based on various scriptural references, particularly from texts like the Bhagavad Gita and the Srimad Bhagavatam, which emphasize Krishna's supremacy. This does not imply a denial of Shiva's significance or reverence but rather positions Shiva within a hierarchy of divine figures, ultimately leading back to Krishna as the Supreme Personality of Godhead.\n\nIt's important to note that different traditions within Hinduism may have varying perspectives on the roles and statuses of deities like Shiva and Krishna, and understanding these differences is key to appreciating the diversity of beliefs within the religion.",
